          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Healthcare websites need provider profiles with photos, credentials, specialties, and treatment philosophy, clear service descriptions for conditions treated and procedures, appointment booking or request system via Calendly/Acuity or phone-based, insurance and payment information showing accepted plans and pricing policies, new patient information on what to expect and bring, location and access details with address and parking, patient resources like forms and educational content, emergency information with clear directive to call 911, professional disclaimers that content is not medical advice, contact information for non-emergency inquiries, telehealth information if offered, and mobile-optimized experience. key: professional presentation, clear provider information, easy booking process, HIPAA-aware practices."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How should healthcare providers handle appointment booking on websites?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For appointment booking, healthcare providers have three main approaches. (1) Integrated booking - Wix Bookings, Squarespace Acuity integration, or Calendly embeds allow patients to book directly. Convenient but requires HIPAA-compliant setup - avoid collecting medical information through booking forms, only collect name, contact, appointment type/purpose. (2) Request system - simple form collects contact info and preferred times, staff follows up to schedule. Safer HIPAA-wise since no medical details collected online. (3) Phone-based - list phone number prominently for appointment scheduling. Most traditional but HIPAA-safest. For therapists and counselors: Calendly or Acuity work well. For medical practices: integrated booking or request forms. For dentists and specialists: booking apps through Wix or Squarespace. Critical: never collect detailed medical information through website forms - that requires HIPAA-compliant systems."
